\begin_layout Standard
The most difficult part of using LaTeX to prepare KUant Guides is that the
 style guideline requires a two column document.
 The two column document is implemented here with the LaTeX package multicol.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multicol package is easy to use, but the two column design worstens
 a couple of problems that can arise in all LaTeX documents.
 Simply put, if the user writes a long equation (or inserts a large graphic),
 the equation (or graphic) is not automatically resized to fit in the column.
 A figure or an equation that is too large for the space will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 out of the column borders.
 That's a common LaTeX problem, but experienced users are aware of it and,
 when the document has only one column, it is easier to navigate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A related problem is that floating figures, a staple of ordinary LaTeX document
 preparation, are not workable.
 One can insert a floating figure in order to obtain a figure label and
 number, but the position must not be allowed to float freely.
 The user should use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

place here definitely
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rubric to force the figure into place.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not necessary to use floats for graphic images.
 A graphic image can be inserted directly, but it is important for the author
 to make sure that the graphic does fit within the space allowed by the
 column.
 That can be done either by editing the graphic file so that its size is
 small--say 3 inches or less--or by using the graphic sizing options in
 the insert graphic option.
 A figure that is inserted into a floating figure may not cause trouble.
 It should be automatically relocated by LaTeX.
\end_layout

